[2026-05-14 14:36:24,137 - mage.rtl_editor - INFO] {"reasoning":"Looking at the remaining simulation failures, I can see that when vibrate_mode=1 and ring=0, the expected motor value is 0 but the actual motor value is 1. This means my current implementation is incorrect.\n\nLet me re-analyze the specification carefully:\n- When vibrate_mode = 1: Turn on the motor (motor = 1) and turn off the ringer (ringer = 0)\n- When vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 1: Turn on the ringer (ringer = 1) and turn off the motor (motor = 0) \n- When vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 0: Turn off both (ringer = 0, motor = 0)\n\nSo looking at the failing case:\n- vibrate_mode = 1, ring = 0\n- Expected: ringer = 0, motor = 0\n- Actual: ringer = 0, motor = 1\n\nWith my current assignments:\n- ringer = (!vibrate_mode) && ring = (1 && 0) = 0 ✓\n- motor = vibrate_mode = 1 ✗ (should be 0)\n\nThe problem is that I'm setting motor = vibrate_mode, but according to the specification, when vibrate_mode = 1, we turn ON the motor, so motor = 1 is correct. However, there might be a misunderstanding in my interpretation.\n\nLet me re-read more carefully:\n\"Whenever the phone needs to ring from an incoming call (input ring), your circuit must either turn on the ringer (output ringer = 1) or the motor (output motor = 1), but not both.\"\n\nSo:\n- If vibrate_mode = 1: motor = 1 (and ringer = 0) \n- If vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 1: ringer = 1 (and motor = 0)\n- If vibrate_mode = 0 and ring = 0: ringer = 0, motor = 0\n\nThis is the correct logic. My motor assignment is actually correct. So let me trace through all cases again:\n\nvibrate_mode=0, ring=0: ringer=(1&&0)=0, motor=0 ✓\nvibrate_mode=0, ring=1: ringer=(1&&1)=1, motor=0 ✓\nvibrate_mode=1, ring=0: ringer=(0&&0)=0, motor=1 ✗ But this should be motor=0!\n\nAh! Now I see the mistake. My interpretation was right, but I misread the requirement. When vibrate_mode=1, we're supposed to turn on the motor and that's it. The motor should be ON when vibrate_mode is 1, reg